    "**Topic:** Regression & Trend Modeling with Seaborn\n",
    "\n",
    "In this notebook, you will explore different regression techniques and visualizations using Seaborn. Regression helps understand relationships between variables and trends over time."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## ðŸ“Œ Topics Covered\n",
    "- Linear Regression\n",
    "- Polynomial Regression\n",
    "- Confidence Intervals\n",
    "- Regression Diagnostics\n",
    "- Using `lmplot()` for Advanced Models"
   ]
  },

  ///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
  ////////////////////////   SECTION 1   ////////////////////////////////
  ///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## ðŸ”¹ 1. Linear Regression\n",
    "Linear regression fits a straight line that best describes the relationship between variables.\n",
    "`sns.regplot()` and `sns.lmplot()` are commonly used."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "\n",
    "tips = sns.load_dataset(\"tips\")\n",
    "\n",
    "sns.regplot(data=tips, x=\"total_bill\", y=\"tip\")\n",
    "plt.title(\"Linear Regression: Total Bill vs Tip\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },

  ///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
  ////////////////////////   SECTION 2   ////////////////////////////////
  ///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## ðŸ”¹ 2. Polynomial Regression\n",
    "Polynomial regression models a curved trend by adding `order=`.\n",
    "`order=2` â†’ quadratic curve."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sns.regplot(data=tips, x=\"total_bill\", y=\"tip\", order=2)\n",
    "plt.title(\"Polynomial Regression (Order 2)\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },

  ///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
  ////////////////////////   SECTION 3   ////////////////////////////////
  ///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## ðŸ”¹ 3. Confidence Intervals\n",
    "Seaborn adds confidence intervals by default.\n",
    "You can remove them using `ci=None` or use new parameter `errorbar=`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sns.regplot(data=tips, x=\"total_bill\", y=\"tip\", ci=95)\n",
    "plt.title(\"Regression with 95% Confidence Interval\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },

  ///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
  ////////////////////////   SECTION 4   ////////////////////////////////
  ///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## ðŸ”¹ 4. Regression Diagnostics\n",
    "Regression diagnostics help analyze residuals (errors) and check model quality.\n",
    "Residual plots show deviations from predicted values."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sns.residplot(data=tips, x=\"total_bill\", y=\"tip\")\n",
    "plt.title(\"Residual Plot\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },

  ///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
  ////////////////////////   SECTION 5   ////////////////////////////////
  ///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## ðŸ”¹ 5. Advanced Modeling with `lmplot()`\n",
    "`lmplot()` is figure-level and supports grouping with `hue`, `row`, `col`, etc.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sns.lmplot(data=tips, x=\"total_bill\", y=\"tip\", hue=\"smoker\")\n",
    "plt.title(\"LMPlot: Regression by Smoker Category\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  }
